    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-11-06T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-11-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="194"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d194">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <persName corresp="#p_RFD1">Roosevelt</persName> Papers: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_HWA2" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">President</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d194fn1">Sent to Washington by the United States Naval
                        Attaché, Moscow, via Navy channels, and forwarded by the White House Map
                        Room to <persName corresp="#p_RFD1">Roosevelt</persName>, who was at his
                        camp, known as “Shangri-la”, in the Catoctin Mountains, Maryland, on
                        November 7, 1943. A copy was sent to the Department of State for its
                        information.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-11-06">November 6,
                            1943</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Personal and secret for the President from <persName corresp="#p_HWA2"
                        >Harriman</persName>.</p>
                <p>I delivered personally your message concerning Turkey<note n="2" xml:id="d194fn2"
                        >See <persName corresp="#p_RFD1">Roosevelt</persName>’s telegram 407,
                        November 4, 1943, to <persName corresp="#p_CC2">Churchill</persName>, <hi
                            rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_151">p. 151</ref>, footnote
                        1.</note> to <persName corresp="#p_MVM1">Molotov</persName> in the form of a
                    letter. <persName corresp="#p_MVM1">Molotov</persName> expressed the highest
                    satisfaction at its contents and offered no objection whatsoever to the proviso
                    which it contained. He proposed that your agreement as expressed in my letter be
                    attached to the protocol concerning Turkey which he and <persName
                        corresp="#p_EA1">Eden</persName> had signed, the text of which I have
                    already cabled you,<note n="3" xml:id="d194fn3">See <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>,
                            <ref target="#pg_148">p. 148</ref>.</note> and that these two documents
                    be made a part of the most secret separate military record of the Conference.
                    His anxiety to have this agreement part of the action of the Conference is I
                    believe due to the fact that he is personally under some criticism by the Soviet
                    military authorities for not obtaining action on this matter at the Conference.
                    I see no objection to his proposal and ask that you authorize me to put it into
                    effect. He discussed the above with the British Ambassador who is cabling
                        <persName corresp="#p_EA1">Eden</persName> for similar authorization.</p>
            </div>
